observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed and acted upon on the recommendations to:
Require the CTO to provide the OCAT with RPTODL for monitoring purposes;
Direct the OCAT and the CTO to coordinate and reconcile discrepancies between recorded balances of RPT and SET Receivable accounts against the total amount of tax delinquencies indicated in the RPTODL;
Direct the OCAT to make a reliable estimate of the City’s bad debts arising from uncollected taxes and set up an allowance for impairment based on the most reliable and available data that the OCAT can obtain;
Require the OCAT to conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis, and validation of receivable accounts; and
Ensure strict adherence to the provisions of Section 37 of IPSAS 3 – Accounting Policies, Changes in Accounting Estimates and Errors in establishing estimates and sufficient proper disclosures to sustain the fair presentation of financial statements under IPSAS 1.

We recommended that Management direct:
The DOA to:
Conduct periodic tax mapping operations and physical surveys to validate whether all real properties are properly recorded;
Fastrack updating of the AR, FAAS, and TDs by assigning additional tax mappers, appraisers, and field personnel; and
Coordinate with the Register of Deeds of the City of Manila for the submission of their latest abstract of registry pursuant to Section 209 of RA No. 7160.
The CTO to:
Intensify the operations of its GIS, i.e., to include other districts of the City, and furnish DOA a copy of the GIS Monitoring Report;
Adopt strategies such as issuance of the warrant of levy, public auction, and institution of civil action against delinquent real property taxpayers;
Request assistance from barangays for its tax campaign program, particularly in the dissemination of NODs and demand letters, and serve warrants of levy to the delinquent real property owners within their areas of jurisdiction;
Regularly post notices of delinquencies in strategic locations of the City Hall, and ask for the assistance of barangays for the posting of the same in each barangay where the delinquent property is located; and
Furnish the City Council with a copy of the NODs for assistance and enforcement purposes.

We recommended that:
The OCAT to –
Provide documentation for inventory adjustments when reconciling the RPCI with accounting records;
Strictly implement the Perpetual Inventory Method through maintenance of SLC;
Coordinate with CGSO on the reconciliation and review of inventory accounts, to include the proper classification of inventories; and
Subsequently, prepare adjusting entries to correct the balances of Inventory accounts based on reconciliations conducted.
The CGSO to –
Observe proper cut-off procedures to ensure that the RPCI reflects correct year-end balances;
Maintain and update stock cards for all inventory items, and ensure that the same are readily available for examination;
Standardize the preparation and submission of SSMI; and
Explore the acquisition of an automated inventory system.
For hospitals to submit and reconcile their records with CGSO on a regular basis.

We recommended and Management agreed and acted upon on the following:
The OCAT to coordinate with CGSO to initiate the reconciliation of the land account details and to establish a fair presentation of the account in the books;
The CGSO to:
Gather data to complete land records and update the inventory listing of land titles;
Secure a fidelity bond for the accountable officer in charge of the safekeeping of the land titles; and
Request the assistance of the Legal Department in evaluating and transferring the TCTs under the name of the City;
The City Budget Office (CBO) to source funds for the procurement of a safety vault and for possible costs of ownership transfer should several properties be deemed as owned by the City.
Strictly comply with the proper recording of PPE accounts guided by Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1, Paragraph 82 of IPSAS 17, Section 125 of the MNGAS, Section 376 of RA No. 7160 and Section 4.4 of Treasury Circular 
No. 2-2009.

We recommended that Management require:
The DEPW to provide OCAT and CGSO complete information of IA-Road Networks, including road IDs, road names, components, descriptions, and cost segregation, to enable the accurate preparation of reports such as the Report on Local Road Network and the Report on Physical Count of the Road Network;
The OCAT to:
Coordinate with DEPW and CGSO to establish the estimated useful life of the depreciable component of road networks and identify road lots;
Coordinate with CGSO to determine the acquisition date for items with incomplete information and update the Road Network Lapsing Schedule;
Recognize the depreciation and accumulated depreciation for the items under road networks using the prescribed chart of accounts; and
Comply with Sections 4 to 8 of COA Circular No. 2015-008, Paragraph 27 IPSAS 1, Paragraph 59 of IPSAS 17.
The Inventory Committee to conduct a comprehensive physical inventory of all road network assets;
The CGSO to prepare the Report on the Local Road Network and the Inventory Committee to submit the Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Network in accordance with Section VI and VII-b of COA Circular No. 2015-008;
The DEPW, CGSO and OCAT to enhance coordination regarding IA-Road Networks; and
The City to comply with pertinent provisions of COA Circular 
No. 2015-008, Paragraph 27 of the IPSAS 1, Paragraph 59 of IPSAS 17.

We recommended that Management direct:
The OCAT and CGSO to initiate reconciliation of their data;
The OCAT to coordinate with the DEPW and establish the cost of demolished school buildings for proper derecognition in the books (with supporting documentation);
The DEPW to fast-track the retrieval of documents pertaining to demolished school buildings, and submit to OCAT and CGSO verified information for updating purposes; and
Strictly comply with Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1, Paragraph 82 of IPSAS 17, Section 147 of COA Circular 92-386 and Section 6.3 of COA Circular 
No. 2020-006.

We recommended that Management require the:
Disposal Committee and CGSO coordinate with the Property Units of the six District Hospitals to facilitate the procedures for disposal of items and updating of the IIRUP and WMR, as guided by COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1, Section 4.7.10 of COA Circular No. 2022-004 and Section 167 of COA Circular No. 92-386;
Disposal Committee and CGSO consider the other modes of disposal provided under Section H of Part II of COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 viable to the six district hospitals and initiate disposal procedures;
OCAT to revisit and reconcile all adjusting entries made in prior years pertaining to the dropping of PPE accounts in the books to account for the items that are no longer recorded; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1, Section 4.7.10 of COA Circular No. 2022-004, and Section 167 of COA Circular No. 92-386.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the OCAT:
To review all dormant accounts and ensure that copies of MOA, Deeds of Donations and other similar documents, Liquidation Reports, Status of Utilization and other documents to support fund transfers are available to determine if project implementations are in compliance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 and ensure that fund balances, if any, are properly accounted for and disposed of in accordance with Section 6.7 of COA Circular No. 94-013;
Together with implementing offices, ensure that MOAs and Deeds of Donation or other similar documents are duly safeguarded in support of transaction recorded in the books;
In case of unavailability of MOAs, Deeds of Donation or other similar documents, immediately coordinate with corresponding NGA grantors/donors to obtain copies thereof; and
Henceforth, ensure that fund transfers and its corresponding MOAs/TAs are strictly monitored.

We recommended that Management:
Require all departments to submit promptly the copies of AIR, DR, SOA, Billing Statements, Progress Billings, and other supporting documents to the OCAT for proper and timely recording of transactions in the books of the City;
Require the OCAT to:
Formulate an effective monitoring system to anticipate and manage the delayed recording of transactions;
Implement clear deadlines and remedial actions to ensure timely accounting of transactions for accurate financial reporting for each period; and
Strictly adhere to the provisions of Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1 and Paragraphs 46 and 47 of IPSAS 3.

We recommended and Management agreed that through the LFC:
Consider revisiting its forecast methodologies to contemplate prior period data, experiences, and relevant events that continue to challenge the City in attaining its revenue targets, and involve Department Heads in the formulation of policy amendments;
Re-evaluate the 2013 Omnibus Revenue Code of the City, enacted through City Ordinance No. 8331, to explore potential amendments to provisions on tax rates, fees, and related regulations;
Require the City Treasurer to accomplish the Quarterly Report of Receipts (LBAc Form No. 1), certified as correct by the City Accountant, to keep track of the revenue generation status;
Engage Department Heads in the conduct of periodic reviews of the Quarterly Report of Receipts to determine whether collection targets are attainable, and to formulate measures that intensify efforts for underperforming income accounts; and
Ensure compliance with Section 316 of RA No. 7160 or LGC 
of 1991 and LBC No. 152 dated August 2, 2023, or the BOM for LGUs 
2023 Edition on the duties and functions of the LFC.

We recommended and Management agreed and acted upon the following:
Reiterate to end-users to promptly comply with the complete documentation of identified PPAs and firmly plan the procurement process;
Conduct EPA to ensure optimal utilization of the fund and to prevent the bidding and awarding of projects close to year-end periods;
Ensure that approved PPAs under the 20% DF are not jeopardized by late reversions/realignments of funds;
Strictly observe the guidelines on the appropriation and utilization of the 20% DF under DILG-DBM JMC No. 2020-1 dated November 4, 2020.

We recommended that Management:
Require the OCAT and CTO to verify and reconcile the amount of 5 percent share due to the DPWH, and remit the same promptly pursuant to the provisions of JMC No. 01, s. 2013;
Require the OBO to formulate a Program of Work for the utilization of the 15 percent OBO share to further improve the efficiency of its operations and to comply with the provisions of PD No.1096 and its IRR and JMC No. 01.

We recommended that Management:
Ensure that approved climate change PPAs are aligned with the City's LCCAP and funded from the City's NTA in accordance with Section 14 of RA No. 9729;
Promptly create the City's LCCAP Core Team in accordance with Paragraph 3.1.1 of DILG-MC No. 2014-135 and Section 7 of the City's LCCAP to facilitate proper planning, prioritization, funding, implementation and monitoring/assessment of proposed climate change PPAs;
Regularly update the LCCAP to ensure its alignment with evolving social, economic, and environmental challenges of the City and Barangays; and
Prepare an Annual Progress Report of the identified PPAs in the LCCAP, submitted to the Climate Change Commission, and furnish a copy to this Office.

We recommended and Management agreed and acted upon:
Hospital Director of the respective District Hospital –
Require the OIC - Medical Records Department, in coordination with the OIC - Information Technology, to formulate a program that will establish a database of electronic/scanned copies of patient records or adopt the E-konsulta system of the DOH for speedy retrieval and availability of patient files to concerned medical departments; and a queuing system that will cater to the OPD;
Adopt the best practices of other City Hospitals, such as conducting information dissemination on health issues to patients during their waiting time and capacitating the health centers to decentralize the volume of patients in the hospitals;
Local Health Board, in coordination with the Hospital Directors to come up with a comprehensive plan to improve the OPD facilities and allocate funding if necessary; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with provisions of the Guidelines in Planning and Design of a Hospital and other Health Facilities relative to addressing hazards in the OPD department; and Hospital Health Information Management Manual 4th Edition (formerly Hospital Medical Records Management Manual) of the DOH relative to the recording, storage, and retrieval of hospital records.

We recommended and the Management agreed that:

The Office of the City Assessor –

Ensure that Assessment Levels and Assessed Values are accurately computed and provided;

Submit to the Auditor’s Office the updated copies of Tax Declaration as proof of corrections/updates made to the 452 RPUs; and

Appraise and assess the RPUs not included in the Assessment Roll and submit copies of tax declaration as proof appraisal and assessment;

Review other tax maps not included in the sample to ensure that RPUs inscribed therein are included in the AR;

Henceforth, ascertain that RPUs in the tax maps are included in the AR; and

The CTO charge and collect from taxpayers the amount of P3,336,539.51 that were under imposed in CY 2023 due to erroneous application of the Assessment Level, and henceforth, ensure that correct amount of taxes is imposed/collected.

We recommended and the Management agreed that:
The Office of the City Assessor –
Ensure that Assessment Levels and Assessed Values are accurately computed and provided;
Submit to the Auditor’s Office the updated copies of Tax Declaration as proof of corrections/updates made to the 452 RPUs; and
Appraise and assess the RPUs not included in the Assessment Roll and submit copies of tax declaration as proof appraisal and assessment;
Review other tax maps not included in the sample to ensure that RPUs inscribed therein are included in the AR;
Henceforth, ascertain that RPUs in the tax maps are included in the AR; and
The CTO charge and collect from taxpayers the amount of P3,336,539.51 that were under imposed in CY 2023 due to erroneous application of the Assessment Level, and henceforth, ensure that correct amount of taxes is imposed/collected.

We recommended that Management:

Consider in the preparation of the City’s annual plan those qualified PPAs to be funded under the PAGCOR fund to fully achieve the objectives and purposes for which the fund was granted;

Consider in the preparation of the City’s annual plan some of the PPAs which could be funded under the PCSO aligned with the intentions/purposes of the fund authorized by the Board of Directors of the said office;

Review the previous years’ PCSO donations to hospitals and Manila Health Department to determine if there are restrictions on the said funds otherwise, consolidate them in the GF; and

Identify the causes/reason for the non-implementation of the Endowment Fund Program of the city hospitals and the non-maintenance of separate depository account required in MOA for Sta Ana Hospital.

Direct the CTO to: 

Produce and submit to the OCAT without further delay all the 288 DVs in Paragraph 1.7 of Observation 
No. 1;

We recommended that Management:
Direct the CTO to:
Produce and submit to the OCAT without further delay all the 
288 DVs specified in para. 1.7;
Maintain a registry of DVs not yet submitted to the OCAT based on the RCI;
Submit to the OCAT within the prescribed period all the DVs supporting the RCI; and
In order to support fully all the checks issued in the RCI 
(a) submit to the OCAT the photocopies of the DVs pertaining to partially paid payrolls and unclaimed checks together with a list of these DVs; and (b) submit every end of the month and directly to the CAO the original DVs once the payrolls are fully paid or the checks are claimed;
Require the OCAT to:
Submit to the CAO without further delay all the 1,684 DVs specified in paragraph 1.5; and
Henceforth, submit to the CAO within the prescribed period all the DVs supporting the checks issued in the RCI together with the list of original DVs still with the CTO, in the proper case, and stop the preparation of a separate schedule of DVs for submission to the CAO; and
In order to avoid retention of DVs and payrolls at the CTO, minimize cash payment, to the greatest extent practicable, by resorting to digital payment through the ATM or similar cash card accounts issued by established financial services providers;
Evaluate and address fully the lack of personnel in the OCAT;
Instruct the CTO and OCAT to recapture the cash for all:
checks that have remained unclaimed for more than six months; and
payrolls that have remained unpaid after 60 days.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the OCAT to:
Indicate in the accounting records the PPE property number for every PPE transaction;
In the absence of documents establishing the acquisition cost of PPE, measure these PPE at fair value and disclose this valuation in the Notes to FS;
Instruct the CGSO to:
Assign a unique property number (PN) for each item of PPE and make this PN a required reference for all PPE transactions to be recognized in the property records;
Indicate in the PPE records the condition of the PPE using common condition  codes;
Require the City Engineering to report timely and regularly to the OCAT and CGSO:
Completed infra-structure projects; and
The cost allocation of PPE items that form part of the contract for building infra-structure projects;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of all the City’s PPE; and
To enable the City to effectively and efficiently track and manage its PPE, develop a property management application system which should be appropriately interfaced with the accounting system and ensure the recording and maintenance of the information necessary for such tracking and management.

We recommended that Management improve the City’s lease management by:
Directing the Committee on Patrimonial Properties to: (a) conduct review of lease contracts; and (b) craft the policies and procedure on lease management embodying the elements enumerated in para. 8.5 and submit the same to the City Council for review and the passing of an ordinance;
Pending the passing of the foregoing ordinance, issuing guidelines on lease administration factoring in those elements in para. 8.5;
Consistent with pertinent laws, rules and regulations on lease, executing contracts or agreements with the 416 lessees mentioned in para. 8.6, with clear provisions that safeguard the City’s interests, ensure the attainment of its financial objectives (like the provision of penalty clause) and meet the service requirements of its constituents;
Providing copies of the executed contracts to the City Auditor’s Office;
Instructing the CGSO-PPD, OCAT and CTO to: (a) maintain all the data on leases vital to effectively manage them and enable compliance with accounting and reporting standards; and (b) regularly reconcile their lease data;
Requiring the CGSO-PPD to: (a) intensify collection of delinquent accounts; and (b) as part of obligation management, conduct periodic lease obligation audit and report the result to Management, Committee on Patrimonial Properties and OCAT for it to act on the accounting implication; and
Directing the OCAT to maintain SLs for each of the lessees indicating therein all the vital information that will enable efficient and effective lease tracking and accounting.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Department of Assessment to:
Rid the RPTAS of input errors;
Correct the 670 under-assessed real properties herein specified in accordance with the realty tax provisions of Ordinance Nos. 8330, as amended, and 8331; and
Provide the CTO a copy of the corrected Assessment Roll;
In order to ensure accuracy and completeness of data and that the RPTAS strictly adopt the realty tax provisions of Ordinance 
Nos. 8331 and 8330, as amended:
Strengthen the RPTAS input controls; and
Consider digitizing the RPT assessment documents, as this will facilitate, among others, efficient data validation and other RPT assessment processing;
Require the CTO to prepare the Certified List of Taxpayers (CLT) based on the corrected Assessment Roll and promptly provide this CLT to the OCAT;
Correct the assessment of the aforementioned 670 RPUs within the parameters set in RA No. 7160;
In order to uphold the principle of uniformity in taxation and increase RPT collection, work on repealing the restriction discussed in paragraph 9.8; and
Improve the collection of RPT, both current and delinquent, at a level materially surpassing the highest collection posted since the implementation of the general revision of real property values.

7.9	We reiterated our recommendation that:
The Management direct the duly created Inventory Committees to timely plan the conduct of thorough and complete physical inventory count of all PPE, prepare the corresponding RPCPPE and reconcile the results of the count with the CGSO and accounting records;
The OCAT and CGSO -
Exhaust all possible means to secure relevant data/information pertaining to the disposed PPE to serve as basis in dropping the same from the books;
Exert extra effort in securing the pertinent documents/information as regards the reported PPE items without cost and those valued at P1.00 to determine its actual acquisition costs for its proper presentation in the RPCPPE; and
Maintain the PPELCs and PCs, respectively, to facilitate the required regular reconciliation of the PPE accounts.

19.5	We recommended that Management direct the officials in charge with assessment and collection of business taxes to intensify further the collection of business taxes and to perform the following courses of actions:
Identify, capture and update in the database all the establishments conducting business within its territorial jurisdiction to serve as reference for the imposition of business taxes, fees and corresponding charges;
Compare data of identified existing establishments in the City against the data of the concerned barangays;
File appropriate charges against business establishments operating without the benefit of permits, in accordance with the provision of the Revenue Code of the City;
Pursue the checking of the database with the information contained in the schedule attached for establishments listed in the barangays to determine businesses operating in the City without the required permits and conduct inspection of establishments if necessary; and
Strictly enforce the requirement of Section 152 of the LGC where barangay clearance is to be submitted by the business establishment before the business tax is paid and permit is issued.

We recommended that:
The CGSO facilitate the preparation and approval of a duly executed Lease Agreement with all existing tenants not covered by contract, indicating therein the terms and conditions agreed upon by the parties, in compliance with Section 198 of COA Circular No. 92-386 and Section 2 of COA Circular No. 88-282A. Henceforth, ensure that all City properties subject for lease are duly supported with approved contracts to safeguard the interest of the City;
The Committee on Patrimonial Properties facilitate the formulation of policy on the management and operations of the leased properties and to immediately submit the same to the City Council for review and the passing of an ordinance, to serve as guide for an efficient and effective administration of the leased patrimonial properties;
The CGSO-PPS -
Intensify the collection of the receivables from the delinquent tenants to generate much needed revenues to fund its priority programs and activities. If warranted, seek the assistance of the CLO for the institution of appropriate legal action to facilitate the collection of the same; and
Regularly provide the OCAT the complete list and amount of uncollected/delinquent rental income duly supported with pertinent reports/information, to serve as bases in recording the same in the books of accounts.

We recommended that Management:
Facilitate the establishment of the GAD M&E system as required in PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 to help and assist the concerned officials in the proper monitoring of the implementation of GAD policies and PPAs and the evaluation of the effectiveness of the same;
Strictly allocate at least five percent of the City's annual budget to fund the implementation of GAD PPAs pursuant to Section 36.a of RA No. 9710. Likewise, we also recommended that GFPS-TWG submit the GPB to the DILG within the prescribed period pursuant to PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01, to facilitate the review and approval of the same;
Facilitate the gathering of data/information needed for the creation of a well-established GAD database to have an accurate and reliable basis in the planning and programming of PPAs as well as in the policy formulation, in order to properly address the existing and emerging GAD issues and concerns;
Facilitate the submission of the draft GAD Code to the City Council for immediate review, deliberation and passing of an ordinance adopting the said Code pursuant to the provisions of PCW Memorandum Circular No. 2009-1 dated September 16, 2009, RA No. 9710 and PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, to serve as guide and support in the proper implementation of GAD;
Direct the GFPS to fully implement the GAD PPAs and monitor their implementation to ensure that optimum benefits are derived by its constituents;
Formulate a GAD plan which conforms to PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, and consider only PPAs which address gender issues so that the intended beneficiaries are assured of the services, protection, and other assistance that the GAD seeks to provide; and
Direct the GFPS and GAD key personnel to undergo capacity building programs and trainings on gender and development to enhance their knowledge and build their competencies on GAD-related laws and international commitments, gender mainstreaming, gender analysis, gender-responsive planning and budgeting, and GAD-related tools among others.
Management comments/actions:
The City Planning and Development Officer informed that recommendation will be made to the proper authorities for the designation of City officials and representatives from DILG and Civil Society Organizations to comprise the Monitoring and Evaluation Team pursuant to the JMC No. 2013-01 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA.
The City Planning and Development Office (CPDO) informed that the composition of the GFPS ExeCom will be immediately reconstituted to include the new chairman of the Appropriation Committee and the newly elected President of the Liga ng mga Barangay. Also requested the NGO Secretariat to submit the names of the representatives from the PWDs Organization, Women Association, Private Sector and the Academe who shall be included as members of the ExeCom. As regards to the designation of the Chair of the TWG, the City GFPS will convene a special meeting for the purpose of electing the Chair of the TWG, as required.
The CPDO explained that the different Department/Offices were requested to submit their respective GPB as early as February 2017 in order to be able to submit the consolidated plan to the DILG within the prescribed period. However, not all of the concerned offices submitted their GPB on time and majority have submitted their budgets short of what was required.
The CPDO had already requested the different departments/offices to provide them of sex-disaggregated data and other relevant information on gender statistics which will be encoded to the existing GAD database being created to serve as basis by the concerned offices in identifying GAD issues and concerns.

We recommended that Management require:

The Office of the City Accountant (OCAT) to –

Prioritize the reconciliation of discrepancies between the book and bank balances of the Cash in Bank accounts and make the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts for identified errors and omissions;

We recommended that:

The CTO initiate the regular/timely release of the quarterly RPT shares for all the barangays of the City pursuant to Section 271(d) of RA No. 7160;
The OCAT submit promptly the pertinent JEVs, DVs and supporting documents to the CAO pertaining to the barangay RPT shares to facilitate the audit and to avoid the suspension of the transaction/s; and
Management – Undertake a review of prior years’ records /documents relative to the consolidation of the 913 barangays as stated in the Factbook of the Liga Ng Mga Barangay, on how the City came up with the 896 existing barangays to serve as basis in the computation and correct distribution of the 30 percent RPT shares;
Conduct an investigation on the circumstances surrounding the allocations of RPT shares to the 27 non-existent barangays and determine the particular barangays where the non-existent/abolished barangays were merged; 
Consider revision of the existing plantilla to include technical positions, such as Certified Public Accountants / accounting graduates, to handle accounting and bookkeeping functions, particularly the timely preparation of the barangay accounting reports and related records; 
The City Treasurer and the City Accountant facilitate the adjustment of their respective barangay records as to the determined actual number of barangays, and review and recompute the RPT shares allocated to the non-existent barangays covering CY 2017 and prior years, for the eventual distribution to all identified existing barangays of the City; 
The Real Property Tax Accounts Division and Barangay Accounts Division (BAD), OCAT, conduct an immediate review and in-depth verification in order to reconcile the reciprocal accounts, Due to LGUs and Due from LGUs, with respect to the barangay RPT shares for the current and prior years to come up with an accurate amount of RPT shares for each of the barangay of the City; and
The BAD fast track the preparation of the books of accounts for CYs 2015 to 2016 for those barangays without FSs and related accounting records submitted to the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:

Refrain from the practice of granting additional CAs to those AOs whose previous CAs were not yet liquidated/settled;
Direct the designated AOs to strictly comply with the rules and regulations particularly on the liquidation of CAs within the prescribed period to ensure that all disbursements are recorded in the books in the appropriate time/period;
Require all City personnel with outstanding CAs who are about to retire, resign or transfer to other agencies to settle their cash and property accountabilities before granting them the necessary clearance;
Require the City Accountant to –
Constantly monitor and remind all AOs to immediately liquidate their outstanding CAs as soon as the purpose for which the same was granted has already been served; and
Whenever applicable condition exists, request for write-off of dormant unliquidated CAs which remained non-moving for 10 years or more and where settlement/collectability could no longer be ascertained in accordance with the guidelines and procedures provided under COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that Management require the MTPB to:

a. Designate qualified City personnel as collectors in lieu of the volunteers or private individuals that will help and assist the CO in the collection of parking fees pursuant to the provisions of Section 65 of the GAAM, Volume I;
b. Require the designated CO to issue the complete set of the parking ticket to the deputized parking aide collectors for them to properly accomplish and indicate relevant information to serve as basis in computing and determining the correct amount of parking fee that should be imposed and collected from the customer/motorists;
d. Facilitate the installation of signages showing the pertinent information and conditions in using the City’s pay parking facility as required under Section 52 of City Ordinance No. 8092 for the awareness of the motorists and the general public and to avoid possible misunderstanding; and
e. Ensure that all collections pertaining to parking fees are accurately and completely reported. Also, intensify collections of parking fees and institute adequate controls and appropriate measures to increase the City’s revenue. Otherwise, consider entering into an agreement with capable and reputable company to handle the operation of the parking facilities under the terms and conditions which are advantageous to the City.

We recommended that Management require:
The OCAT to –
Prioritize the reconciliation of discrepancies between the book and bank balances of the Cash in Bank accounts and make the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts for identified errors and omissions;
Provide details for expropriation accounts with SL balances presented in lump sum;
Coordinate with the City Treasurer on the possibility of maintaining only a few bank accounts and the closure of those no longer necessary after completion of the analysis and reconciliation;
Properly prepare and maintain an updated GL and SL, in hard and soft copies, and make available for review by the Audit Team at any given period;
Provide the details or relevant data of all the transactions posted in the   SL to facilitate review and reconciliation with the controlling accounts in the City’s books of accounts; and
Ensure that all JEVs drawn are supported with the necessary documents and the same are submitted to the Audit Team within the prescribed period to avoid the suspension of the transactions.
The Office of the City Treasurer (OCT) and OCAT to exert concerted efforts to review and analyze their respective records to come up with reconciled and correct balances; and
The OCT to specify in the maintained Cashbooks the corresponding bank account number to facilitate the reconciliation with accounting records and for proper monitoring.

We recommended that:
The OCT initiate the regular/timely release of the quarterly RPT shares for all the barangays of the City pursuant to Section 271(d) of R.A. 7160;
The OCAT submit promptly the pertinent JEVs, DVs and supporting documents to the CAO pertaining to the barangay RPT shares to facilitate    the audit and to avoid the suspension of the transaction/s.
Management –
Undertake a review of  prior years’ records/documents relative to               the consolidation of  the 913 barangays as stated in the Factbook of the Liga Ng Mga Barangay, on how the City came up with the 896 existing barangays to serve as basis in the computation and correct distribution of the 30 percent RPT shares;
Conduct an investigation on the circumstances surrounding the allocations of RPT shares to the 27 non-existent  barangays and   determine the particular barangays where the non-existent/abolished barangays were merged;
Make representation with the LBP,  Tayuman branch, to establish the legitimacy of the bank account maintained for Barangay 10 and  determine whether the RPT shares deposited are still intact;
Consider revision of the existing plantilla to include technical positions, such as Certified Public Accountants/accounting graduates, to handle accounting and bookkeeping functions, particularly the timely  preparation of the barangay accounting reports and related records; and
The City Treasurer and the City Accountant facilitate the adjustment of their respective barangay records as to the determined actual number of   barangays, and review and recompute the RPT shares allocated to the non-existent barangays covering  CY 2017 and prior years, for the eventual distribution to all identified existing barangays of the City;
The Real Property Tax Accounts Division and Barangay Accounts Division (BAD), OCAT, conduct an immediate review and in-depth verification in order to reconcile the reciprocal accounts, Due to LGUs and Due from   LGUs, with respect to the barangay RPT shares for the current and prior   years to come up with an accurate amount of RPT shares for each of the barangay of the City; and
The BAD fast track the preparation of the books of accounts for CYs 2015   to 2016 for those barangays without financial statements and related accounting records submitted to the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:
Refrain from the practice of granting additional cash advances to those AOs whose previous cash advances were not yet liquidated/settled;
Direct the designated AOs to strictly comply with the rules and regulations particularly on the liquidation of cash advances within the prescribed period as required under COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
Require all City personnel with outstanding cash advances who are about to retire, resign or transfer to other agency to settle first their cash and property accountabilities before granting them the necessary clearance; and
Require the City Accountant to:
Constantly monitor and remind all AOs to liquidate their outstanding   cash advances as required to avoid accumulation of outstanding cash advances;
Order the withholding of any amount due to all AOs who failed to liquidate their outstanding cash advances despite demand and coordinate with the City Legal Office for the institution of appropriate legal action;
Effect the immediate recording of the cash advance granted to Ms. Leonora Pascual intended for PCF which was inadvertently not recorded in the books of accounts; and
Request for write-off of dormant unliquidated cash advances granted to disbursing officers, agency officials and employees which remained    non-moving for 10 years or more and where settlement/collectability could no longer be ascertained in accordance with the guidelines and procedures provided under COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that Management:
Formulate policies and designate a responsible officer to ensure strict enforcement of the terms and conditions of the contract to sell and make the necessary action to take possession of the units and/or recover the uncollected amortizations from the delinquent buyers;
Require the PPS to investigate cases of transferred and sub-leased condominium units and take the necessary action to repossess these units;
Offer for sale all of the 30 parking slots to interested and qualified unit owners and require the OCAT to recognize the cost of the parking lots in the books of accounts; and
The OIC, CGSO provided explanations on the noted observations and informed the Audit team of the following courses of action to be adopted by that Office, to wit:
Closely coordinate with the City Legal Office for the strict enforcement of the terms and conditions stipulated in the Contract to sell;
Formulate policies and undertake necessary steps to conform with existing laws for amicable settlement and peaceful takeover of units from delinquent tenants;
Send final demand letters to all delinquent tenants/buyers providing information on possible filing of civil and/or administrative charges for non-payment of amortizations;
Create an investigation team to gather evidence in connection with the alleged illegal sub-lease and sale of the condominium units. The result of investigation shall be the basis in the filing of administrative and civil action before the proper authorities and to implement eviction of delinquent tenants; and
Recommend to the City Legal Office the possible filing of action under Specific Performance against the Suntrust Properties, Inc. in connection with the titling of 30 parking slots to be disposed of through sale.

We recommended that Management require the MTPB to:
Designate qualified City personnel as collectors in lieu of the volunteers or private individuals that will help and assist the CO in the collection of parking fees pursuant to the provisions of Section 65 of the GAAM, Volume I;
Establish proper control measures to ensure that the appropriate amount of parking fees are imposed and collected from motorists and eventually remitted intact to the CTO in order to maximize the collection of the City’s revenue;
Require the designated CO to issue the complete set of the parking ticket to the deputized parking aide collectors for them to properly accomplish and indicate relevant information to serve as basis in computing and determining the correct amount of parking fee that should be imposed and collected from the customer/motorists;
Facilitate the installation of signages showing the pertinent information and conditions in using the City’s pay parking facility as required under Section 52 of City Ordinance No. 8092 for the awareness of the motorists and the general public and to avoid possible misunderstanding; and
Ensure that all collections pertaining to parking fees are accurately and completely reported. Also, intensify collections of parking fees and institute adequate controls and appropriate measures to increase the City’s revenue. Otherwise, consider entering into an agreement with capable and reputable company to handle the operation of the parking facilities under the terms and conditions which are advantageous to the City.

We recommended that Management require:
The GAD Focal Person to adhere strictly to the requirements of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01 in the preparation of the GPB and to submit the same to the DILG;
The GFPS ensure that the GPB was reviewed and approved by the DILG Regional Office for integration in the Annual Investment Program, Local Expenditure Program, Budget Expenditure and Sources of Financing, and in the Executive Budget pursuant Items 4.1.C.1.3 and 4.1.C.1.7 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01;
All heads of departments/offices to include PPAs and budget for GAD related activities in their respective Annual Investment Programs to mainstream GAD in their regular activities; and
The GFPS to ensure that the GPB includes all GAD-related PPAs and presents the gender issues, their causes and the related objectives to improve the likelihood that PPAs are responsive to the issues and address the causes.
